{
  "doc_id": "15458",
  "text": "The functional significance of the N terminus of cTnT is demonstrated by the findings that deletions in the N terminus of cTnT attenuate thin filament activation by depressing both Ca 2+ -activated maximal tension [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and myofilament Ca 2+ sensitivity [CITATION_5] . Deletions in the N terminus of cTnT have been shown to alter Tn-Tm interactions [CITATION_6] , as well as Tn-Tm interaction with actin [CITATION_7] . In view of the observation that cardiac contractile dynamics are tuned by a significant interplay between Tn isoforms and MHC [CITATION_8] , and that -and -MHC isoforms divergently affect thin filament activation [CITATION_9] , we sought to determine how the impact of deletions in the N terminus of cTnT is modified by a shift from -to -MHC background. An in teresting observation in the present study is that the at tenuating effect of RcTnT 1-43 on Ca 2+ -activated maximal tensionobserved under an -MHC background [CITATION_10] -is suppressed by a shift to -MHC background (Fig. 3, A and B) . Specifically, RcTnT 1-43 attenuates maximal tension by 46% under an -MHC background (Fig. 3 A) , whereas a shift to -MHC background attenuates maximal tension by only 18% (Fig. 3 B) . Thus, our data demonstrate that RcTnT 1-43 attenuates thin filament activation to a greater extent in the presence of -MHC.",
